text: Unusual features of the large linear plasmid pSA3239 from Streptomyces aureofaciens CCM 3239 Erik Mingyar, Renata Novakova, Renata Knirschova, Lubomira Feckova, Carmen Bekeova, Jan Kormanec Institute of Molecular Biology, Slovak Academy of Sciences, 845 51 Bratislava, Slovak Republic Keywords: Streptomyces Plasmid Replication Secondary metabolites Telomere Gram-positive soil bacteria of the genus Streptomyces are one of the main producers of bioactive natural products, including many anti- biotics. They undergo a complex process of morphological diﬀerentia- tion, accompanied by a so-called “physiological diﬀerentiation” invol- ving the production of biologically active secondary metabolites. The biosynthetic genes of these secondary metabolites are physically clus- tered and are located in large (6.6 to 11 Mb) chromosomes, which unlike those of most other bacteria, are linear (Hopwood, 2007). In addition to linear chromosomes, Streptomyces species frequently contain linear plasmids, ranging in size from 12 kb to 1.8 Mb (Kirby and Chen, associated protein; TIR, terminal inverted repeat; TP, terminal proteins https://doi.org/10.1016/j.gene.2017.11.046 Received 4 October 2017; Received in revised form 13 November 2017; Accepted 15 November 2017 Available online 17 November 2017 0378-1119/ © 2017 Elsevier B.V. We previously identiﬁed the aur1 gene cluster, responsible for the production of the angucycline antibiotic auricin in Streptomyces aureofaciens CCM 3239. Pulse-ﬁeld gel electrophoresis showed a single, 241 kb linear plasmid, pSA3239, in this strain, and several approaches conﬁrmed the presence of the aur1 cluster in this plasmid. We report here the nucleotide sequence of this 241,076-bp plasmid. pSA3239 contains an un- precedentedly small (13 bp) telomeric sequence CCCGCGGAGCGGG, which is identical to the conserved Palindrome I sequence involved in the priming of end-patching replication. A bioinformatics analysis revealed 234 open reading frames with high number (28) of regulatory genes from various families. In contrast to most other linear plasmids, pSA3239 contains a pair of replication initiation genes (sa76 and sa75) located at its extreme left end, adjacent to the telomere. Together with similar proteins from several other linear plasmids (pFRL2, pSLA2-M, pSV2, pSDA1, and SAP1), they constitute a new family of replication initiation proteins. This left end also contains two genes, tpgSa and tapSa, encoding the terminal protein and the telomere associated- protein involved in telomere end-patching replication. pSA3239 also contains two genes homologous to the parAB partitioning system, and deletion of the parA homologue (sa43) aﬀects structural stability of the plasmid. pSA3239 carries ﬁve potential secondary metabolite gene clusters. In addition to aur1 and a non-ribosomal peptide synthase (NRPS) gene cluster for the blue pigment indigoidine, it also contains a partial type II poly- ketide synthase (PKS) gene cluster, a partial type I PKS gene cluster, and a NRPS/PKSI gene cluster for unknown secondary metabolites. The last gene cluster contains a subcluster of seven genes (sa91–sa97), highly similar to part of the valanimycin biosynthetic cluster vlm. A S. aureofaciens strain lacking pSA3239 was prepared. This deletion did not substantially

unknown secondary metabolites. The last gene cluster contains a subcluster of seven genes (sa91–sa97), highly similar to part of the valanimycin biosynthetic cluster vlm. A S. aureofaciens strain lacking pSA3239 was prepared. This deletion did not substantially aﬀect growth and diﬀerentiation. A comparative analysis of secondary metabolites between both strains did not identify any product, except auricin and indigoidine, which is dependent upon pSA3239. Thus, the other three identiﬁed gene clusters are likely silent under these conditions.

This may ensure the eﬃcient pro- pagation of these genes in the soil bacteria population via horizontal gene transfer (Kinashi, 2011). The Streptomyces linear chromosomes and plasmids have similar features. They both have terminal inverted repeats (TIR) at both ends, the sizes of which range from 44 bp to about 1 Mb, and are capped by terminal proteins (TP) covalently bound to their DNA 5′ ends (Kirby and Chen, 2011). Like the Streptomyces chromosomes, replication of the linear plasmids usually starts at centrally located replication origins and continues bidirectionally towards both ends, leaving single-stranded overhangs at the 3′ ends (Chang and Cohen, 1994). These 3′ end overhangs contain several tightly-packed palindromic sequences cap- able of forming stable secondary structures. For most Streptomyces tel- omeres, these palindromic sequences (Palindromes I to VI) are highly conserved, with the 13 bp of Palindrome I being invariant, and they constitute an archetypal family of typical telomeres. These telomeric overhangs are ﬁlled by DNA synthesis carried out by a telomere-asso- ciated protein (Tap) using TP as the primer in a unique priming process termed ‘end patching’. The propagation of Streptomyces replicons in a linear form strictly requires both Tap and TP. During this ‘end patching’ process, Tap tightly binds Palindrome II and III, concomitantly re- cruiting TP to the telomere complex. Tap subsequently deox- ynucleotidylates TP using Palindrome I as a template, and after syn- it leaves the thesizing the 13 nt complementary to Palindrome I, complex. These 13 nt acts as a DNA primer for other DNA polymerases to ﬁll in the remaining gap (Huang et al., 1998; Kirby and Chen, 2011; Yang et al., 2015).

As in other bacteria, replication initiation of the Streptomyces chromosomes begins at the origin of replication oriC. The replication is initiated through the cooperative binding of the initiator protein DnaA to multiple DnaA-recognition sites within the oriC region. This triggers separation of the DNA strands, providing an entry site for a helicase and later the other replication enzymes, (e.g. primase and DNA Pol III) re- sponsible for DNA synthesis (Wolanski et al., 2015). Unlike the chro- mosomes, the replication origins and required initiation proteins vary widely among the diﬀerent Streptomyces linear plasmids. The ﬁrst characterized replication locus for a linear plasmid was for pSLA2. It is centrally located and composed of iterons (a series of short, direct re- peats) located within the essential genes rep1 (encoding a DNA-binding protein) and rep2 (encoding a DNA helicase) (Chang et al., 1996). Si- milar rep loci (helicase/iteron) were also found in pSCL1, SCP1, SLP2, and pSHK1 (Chang et al., 1996; Redenbach et al., 1999; Xu et al., 2006; Zhang et al., 2009). Two other linear plasmids, pSLA2-L and pSCL2 also contain iterons and two homologous genes (repL1, repL2, and repC1 and repC2, respectively), but these encode hypothetical proteins with no similarity to the rep1 and rep2 genes from the other linear plasmids (Hiratsu et al., 2000; Wu et al., 2006). Finally, three diﬀerent replica- tion loci consisting of an essential non-coding sequence (ncs) and novel replication initiation genes, have been identiﬁed in the Streptomyces linear plasmids pRL2, pRL4, and pFRL2. Together, these three diﬀerent cases show that the replication loci of Streptomyces linear plasmids possess a surprising variety of components, positions and combinations (Zhang et al., 2009).

We previously identiﬁed a polyketide synthase gene cluster, aur1, responsible for producing the angucycline antibiotic auricin in Streptomyces aureofaciens CCM 3239 (Kormanec et al., 2014). The aur- icin cluster is interrupted by another secondary metabolite cluster for the production of the blue pigment indigoidine (Novakova et al., 2010). We showed that the aur1 cluster is located on the large linear plasmid pSA3239 (Novakova et al., 2013). The aim of the present study was the complete sequencing and bioinformatics analysis of pSA3239. We re- port here the complete nucleotide sequence of pSA3239, and the characterization of its telomeres and the genes involved in its replica- tion, segregation and production of secondary metabolites. In addition, we prepared a S. aureofaciens strain lacking pSA3239 and investigated its secondary metabolite production in comparison with that of the wild-type S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 strain. 2.1. Bacterial strains, plasmids and culture conditions S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 wild-type was from the Czech Collection of Microorganisms (Brno, Czech Republic). The E. coli DH5α strain (Stratagene) was used as a host, and the plasmid pBluescript II SK- (Stratagene) was used for E. coli cloning experiments. E. coli cosmid SuperCos-1 (Evans et al., 1989) was from Stratagene. E. coli BW25113/ pIJ790 was used as a host for PCR-targeted gene disruption using the apramycin resistance plasmid pIJ773, and E. coli ET12567/pUZ8002 was used as a nonmethylating host (Gust et al., 2003). The growth of S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 strains was carried out in rich Bennet medium (Horinouchi et al., 1983) as described in Kutas et al. (2013). E. coli growth and transformation conditions were as described by Ausubel et al. (1995).

Standard DNA manipulations in E. coli were carried out as described in Ausubel et al. (1995), and those in Streptomyces according to Kieser et al. (2000). Chromosomal DNA from S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 was isolated according to Kieser et al. (2000). Southern blot hybridization analysis was performed on Hybond-N nylon membranes (Amersham) with digoxigenin (DIG)-labelled DNA probes, and hybridization and detection were done according to the protocols provided by the man- ufacturer (Roche). Colony blot hybridization was done as described in Ausubel et al. (1995). The S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 cosmid library (Sau3AI partially-digested 32–42 kb DNA fragments in the BamHI site of SuperCos-1; Novakova et al., 2010) was spread on Hybond-N mem- brane (Amersham), plated on LB medium with 100 μg/ml ampicillin, and grown overnight at 37 °C. Replica membranes were hybridized with random-primed DIG-labelled DNA probes (Roche). 2.3. DNA sequencing of pSA3239

The nucleotide sequence of pSA3239 was determined using a chromosome-walking procedure. The S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 cosmid library was hybridized with a DIG-labelled probe comprising approxi- mately 1 kb end DNA fragments from each successively identiﬁed cosmid. Representative recombinant cosmids containing the largest unknown region were used for sequencing. Employing internal re- striction sites, the DNA fragments were cloned into pBluescript II SK + and the resulting fragments were sequenced from both ends. Nucleotide sequencing was carried out with the ABI PRISM™ Dye Terminator Cycle Sequencing Ready Reaction Kit (Applied Bio-systems) and analyzed using an Applied Biosystems model 373 DNA analyzer. Telomere ends were sequenced according to Ohnishi et al. (2008) using a polyA tailing/nested PCR method. PolyA tails were attached to the 3c ends of S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 chromosomal DNA using terminal deox- ynucleotidyl transferase. This modiﬁed DNA was used as a template for PCR using primers TIR1Rev (5′-CCTGTTTCTCAGCCAGCAGCACC-3′) and polyT1 (5′-GTAAAACGACGGCCAGTATAGGGTTTTTTTTTTTT-3′) for the left terminal region of pSA3239, and primers TIR2Rev (5′-CGT TCCGCACCGCAGAAGGGCAGG-3′) and polyT1 for the right terminal region of pSA3239. Ampliﬁed fragments were used for nested PCR using primers TIR1Rev2 (5′-CCGACGAGCGAAGCGAGGTTTCC-3′) and polyT2 (5′-GTAAAACGACGGCCAGTATAGG-3′) for the left terminal region of pSA3239, and primers TIR2Rev2 (5′-GGTCAAGCACAACTCC GACCTGC-3′) and polyT2 for the right terminal region. The resulting PCR-ampliﬁed DNA fragments were gel-puriﬁed and sequenced using the T

primers TIR2Rev2 (5′-GGTCAAGCACAACTCC GACCTGC-3′) and polyT2 for the right terminal region. The resulting PCR-ampliﬁed DNA fragments were gel-puriﬁed and sequenced using the TIR1Rev2 and TIR2Rev2 primers, respectively. The connected nu- cleotide sequence (241,076 bp) of pSA3239 has been deposited in GenBank under accession number KJ396772.

2.4. Disruption of the S aureofaciens CCM 3239 sa43 gene The PCR targeted REDIRECT procedure (Gust et al., 2003) was used to delete the sa43 gene encoding the parA homologue in S. aureofaciens CCM 3239. The apramycin resistance cassette was PCR ampliﬁed using primers sa43DIR (5′-CGCCCACATGCACCCAAGAACGTTAGTAAAGTCC CTCTCATTCCGGGGATCCGTCGACC-3′) and sa43rev (5′-GGGCGAAG- GAAGCCGA- TACCCCGAGCTTGTCGGCCTTGCTGTAGGCTGGAGCTGCTT C-3′) using the plasmid pIJ773 as a template. Correct replacement of the sa43 coding region in the resulting derived cosmid pCosSA31-sa43::AmR was veriﬁed by restriction mapping. The cosmid pCosSA31-sa43::AmR was transformed into the non-methylating E. coli ET12567/pUZ8002 strain and introduced into to S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 by conjugation; mutants resistant

apramycin and sensitive to kanamycin were selected. One apramycin- resistant and kanamycin-sensitive colony was identiﬁed, and the cor- rect double crossover event of the mutant strain S. aureofaciens Δsa43 was conﬁrmed by Southern-blot hybridization (Fig. S1). 2.5. Pulse-ﬁeld gel electrophoresis (PFGE) The preparation of DNA samples from Streptomyces mycelium im- mobilized in agarose, and the subsequent PFGE were done essentially as described previously (Novakova et al., 2013). Treated DNA samples were subjected to PFGE on 0.8% agarose using a Rotaphor System (Biometra) under the following conditions: a 30–5 s logarithmic ramp time, and a 180–120 V logarithmic voltage ramp in 0.25 × TAE buﬀer at 10 °C for 23 h. Ladders of linear lambda concatemers (Bio-Rad) were used as molecular weight markers, and gels were stained with ethidium bromide. Southern blot hybridization analysis of the PFGE gel was then carried out with DIG-labelled DNA probes as described in Ausubel et al. (1995). 2.6. Preparation of S. aureofaciens Del-LP strain

A strain lacking pSA3239 was prepared by the selection of sponta- neously appearing apramycin-sensitive clones from several S. aur- eofaciens mutant strains, in which the auricin genes aur1PR3, sagA, sagR, sa46, sa53, sa59, sa52, had been replaced by an apramycin-re- sistance gene (Bekeova et al., 2016; Mingyar et al., 2015; Novakova et al., 2011). Each strain was sporulated three times on solid Bennet medium without any antibiotic. The ﬁnal spore stocks were spread on solid Bennet medium in dilution to distinguish individual colonies. Colonies were analyzed for apramycin sensitivity by parallel spreading on Bennet media with and without apramycin. After examining thou- sands of colonies, one apramycin-sensitive colony was identiﬁed. The corresponding strain was named S. aureofaciens Del-LP. The absence of pSA3239 was conﬁrmed by PFGE followed by Southern blot hy- bridization with DIG-labelled probes from three diﬀerent pSA3239 positions (left-end, center, right end). Likewise, a standard Southern blot hybridization of total chromosomal DNA prepared from S. aur- eofaciens Del-LP digested with several enzymes was performed to con- ﬁrm the deletion of pSA3239. 2.7. Analysis of secondary metabolites

Spores (4 × 109 cfu) of S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 and S. aur- eofaciens Del-LP were inoculated into 50 ml Bennet medium in 250 ml Erlenmeyer ﬂasks, and the cultures grown on an orbital shaker at 270 rpm and 28 °C. 5 ml aliquots were taken from the cultures at par- ticular time points (14, 18, 22, 39, 46, 70, 92, 120 h). Secondary me- tabolites, including auricin, were extracted by ethyl acetate and ana- lyzed by TLC, followed by biochromatography and HPLC as described previously (Kutas et al., 2013). In brief, extracted samples were dis- solved in 100 μl of 96% (v/v) ethanol and 10 μl aliquots were subjected to TLC analysis on silica gel 60 F254 plates (Merck) with n-butanol sa- turated with water. Dried TLC plates were analyzed by biochromato- graphy with soft nutrient agar (Kieser et al., 2000) containing fresh Bacillus subtilis and Escherichia coli cultures. The plates were incubated for 16 h at 37 °C and visually screened for growth-inhibition zones. HPLC analysis of 10 μl samples was performed on an OmmiSpher 5 C18 column (5 μm, 250 × 4.6 mm, Varian, Lake Forest, CA) using a Shi- madzu LC-10A HPLC system with a SPD-20A UV-VIS detector (Shi- madzu, Japan) with acetonitrile and 0.5% (v/v) acetic acid in water as the mobile phase and detection at 210 and 254 nm. Elution was carried out with a linear acetonitrile gradient from 20 to 100% for 30 min at a ﬂow rate of 1 ml/min. 3. Results and discussion 3.1. Sequencing and basic analysis of pSA3239

We previously identiﬁed a 240-kb linear plasmid, pSA3239, con- taining a gene cluster for the angucycline antibiotic auricin, in S. aur- eofaciens CCM 3239 (Novakova et al., 2013). In order to sequence the whole plasmid, a cosmid library containing S. aureofaciens CCM3239 genomic DNA in a SuperCos-1 cosmid (Novakova et al., 2010) was screened with a DIG-labelled probe covering the region at the beginning of the DNA fragment of cosmid pCosSA25 (Fig. 1), which holds the upstream part of the auricin cluster (Mingyar et al., 2015). Restriction mapping followed by hybridization analyses of identiﬁed positive cos- mids revealed overlapping DNA fragments with the best representative, the pCosSA31 cosmid, containing the largest region upstream of the aur1 cluster. A similar chromosome-walking strategy was used to identify the following overlapping representative cosmid, pCosSA74 (Fig. 1). Further screening of the cosmid library with the labelled DNA end fragment from pCosSA74 failed to identify a larger DNA region. Moreover, Southern blot hybridization of S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 chromosomal DNA, digested using several restriction enzymes, with the labelled DNA end fragment of pCosSA74, produced identical hy- bridizing DNA fragments (data not shown), indicating that the begin- ning of the DNA fragment of pCosSA74 is close to the left end of pSA3239. A similar chromosome-walking strategy was used with a DIG- labelled probe covering the region at the end of the DNA fragment of pCosSA19 (Fig. 1), which contained the downstream part of the auricin cluster (Novakova et al., 2010). Likewise, restriction mapping and hy- identiﬁed the best bridization analyses cosmid, pCosSA68, which contained the largest region downstream of the aur1 cluster. A similar chromosome-walking strategy was then used to identify the successive overlapping representative cosmids pCosSA91, pCosSA106, and pCosSA136 (Fig. 1). contained the largest region downstream of the aur1 cluster. A similar chromosome-walking strategy was then used to identify the successive overlapping representative cosmids pCosSA91, pCosSA106, and pCosSA136 (Fig. 1). Chromosome-walking screening of the cosmid library with the labelled end fragment of DNA from pCosSA136 likewise failed to identify a larger DNA region, and Southern blot hybridization analysis of S. aureofaciens CCM3239 chro- mosomal DNA indicated that the end of the pCosSA136 DNA fragment is close to the right end of pSA3239. The nucleotide sequence from both strands was determined after subcloning DNA fragments based on a detailed restriction analysis of the identiﬁed cosmids (Materials and methods).

The missing telomeric ends were sequenced using a polyA tailing/ nested PCR method (Ohnishi et al., 2008) using primers from left and right ends of the determined pSA3239 sequence (Materials and methods). In both cases, as suggested by hybridization analysis, we extended the pSA3239 sequence by about 100 bp (left end) and 300 bp (right end). The assembled nucleotide sequence of pSA3239 contained 241,076 bp with an overall G + C content of 72.12%, comparable to the Streptomyces genomes (Bentley et al., 2002; Ohnishi et al., 2008). A sequence analysis using the CODON PREFERENCE program identiﬁed 234 ORFs having a codon usage typical for Streptomyces genes (Wright and Bibb, 1992). The putative gene products were screened against various sequence databases, revealing possible functions for the pre- dicted ORF products. The results are presented graphically in Fig. 1 and summarized in Table S1. 3.2. Telomere structure of pSA3239 The ends of the Streptomyces linear plasmids and chromosomes contain long inverted repeats (TIRs) ranging from 44 bp to about 1 Mb. These are covalently bound to terminal proteins (TPs) which are used to prime the end-patching replication of the single-stranded telomeres, typically about 250–320 bp long, which are left at the DNA 3′ ends after standard bi-directional replication (normally initiated from an internal origin). These telomeres contain palindromic sequences capable of forming complex secondary structure; this structure appears to be

Fig. 2. Structural features of the terminal sequences of pSA3239. (a) Comparison of the ﬁrst 400 nucleotides of the left and right terminal sequences. Identical nucleotides in the alignment are shaded in black. Arrows with Roman numerals indicate palindromic sequences. The open boxes mark the asymmetrical center of each palindrome. (b) The secondary structures of the 3′-terminal 105 nucleotides of the left and right terminal sequences of pSA3239 predicted by Mfold (Zuker, 2003). Roman numerals indicate the palindromes seen in the alignment. essential for replication and the protection of the ends of the linear genome (Huang et al., 1998; Kirby and Chen, 2011; Yang et al., 2015). Comparing the left and right terminal sequences of pSA3239 (Fig. 2a) revealed extremely short TIRs of only 13 bp, followed by several short patches of homology up to position 101. This is, to our knowledge, the shortest TIR so far identiﬁed for a Streptomyces genome or linear plasmid. Despite the diﬀerences in the primary sequences, the predicted secondary structures of both ends were strikingly similar, with the highest homology appearing in ﬁve predicted hairpin structures (Fig. 2b).

The majority of Streptomyces telomeres are grouped into a highly conserved archetypal family containing several palindromic sequences (Palindromes I to VI). Palindrome I, the ﬁrst 13 bp, is highly conserved, and is used as a template for end-patching by Tpg-Tap system (Yang et al., 2015). The remaining palindromes are also conserved, but less so. The minimum length of the telomere needed for end-patching replica- tion is 144 nt, which covers the ﬁrst six palindromes. In many cases Palindrome I is complementary to the internal Palindrome IV, though this pairing is not necessary for end-patching replication. Palindromes I, II, III, and V are essential for this process, however. Most of the loops formed by the palindromes contain a GNA triplet, which are refractory to nuclease attack (Huang et al., 1998; Kirby and Chen, 2011). Com- paring the terminal sequences of pSA3239 with several representative telomeres of the archetypal family revealed that they do belong to this family (Fig. 3), but that they contain only the ﬁrst ﬁve essential pa- lindromes, and a partially degenerated Palindrome VI. They also lack the Palindrome I to IV pairing. Their hairpin sequences contain the typical GNA loops, and the extremely short TIR of pSA3239 is identical to the 13 nt of Palindrome I sequence that is essential for end-patching. Both pSA3239 telomeres are conserved in the two regions containing Palindromes II and III, which are bound by the telomere-associated protein Tap during the end-patching (Bao and Cohen, 2003; Yang et al., 2015). 3.3. Replication, segregation, and terminal binding protein genes

Streptomyces linear chromosomes and plasmids replicate bi-direc- tionally from an internal origin towards the telomeres (Chang and Cohen, 1994), leaving single-stranded overhangs at the 3′ ends, which are patched to restore the double helix by the TP-Tap system, which is primed by TP. TPs are encoded by the tpg genes, which constitute an operon together with the tap gene encoding Tap (Yang et al., 2015). In many linear plasmids (e.g. pSLA2, SCP1, SLP2, pSCL1, pSHK1), the origin of replication contains an internal region consisting of short di- rect repeats (iterons) together with an adjacent rep gene encoding a DNA helicase (Kirby and Chen, 2011; Zhang et al., 2009). bioinformatics analysis revealed no typical iteron-rep locus in the whole pSA3239 sequence, but did identify two translationally-coupled genes, sa76 and sa75, in the region adjacent to the left telomere (Fig. 1), en- coding proteins with high similarity to the replication initiation pro- teins pFRL2.1 (pFRL2_102c) and pFRL2.2 (pFRL2_101c) from of the pFRL2 linear plasmid of Streptomyces sp. FR1 (GenBank Acc. No. NC_ 023282). In that plasmid, these two genes, together with an adjacent 750-bp non-coding sequence (ncs) function as a replication origin (Zhang et al., 2009). A Blast search using the Sa76 and Sa75 proteins returned several homologues from the Streptomyces linear plasmids pSLA2-M (Yang et al., 2011; GenBank Acc. No. AB597522), pSV2 (Spatz et al., 2002; GenBank Acc. No. AY211023), pSDA1 (Jankowitsch et al., 2012; GenBank Acc. No. HE971710), and SAP1 (Ikeda et al., 2003; GenBank Acc. No NC_004719). In all cases, the corresponding genes were also translationally-coupled and located adjacent the telomere (Fig. 4), meaning they all likely constitute previously-characterized telomere-adjacent replication loci (Zhang et al., 2009). A search of the Pfam database showed that both proteins contain a DNA-binding helix- turn-helix domain, Sa76 at residues 101–149 (Pfam 13545) and Sa75 at residues 18–72 (Pfam13730) (Fig. 4), suggesting that both replication initiation proteins interact with DNA.

In addition to pFRL2, Streptomyces sp. FR1 also contains linear plasmid pFRL1, which contains two internal origins of replication, one of which is located in the telomere-adjacent region, like those in the linear plasmids above (Zhang et al., 2010). Interestingly, although the two replication initiation genes located in this region, pFRL1.1 and pFRL1.2, have no homology to the sa76 and sa75 homologues, the au- thors did ﬁnd a 231-bp non-coding sequence adjacent to them, which has strong similarity with the non-coding sequences of pFRL2, pSV2, and SAP1. They also conﬁrmed its role in replication (Zhang et al., 2010). Our bioinformatics analysis of an 800 bp region upstream of each replication initiation protein showed that all the homologous non- coding sequences in the telomere-adjacent replication loci of pFRL2, pSLA2-M, pSV2, pSDA1, and SAP1 also contain this conserved region. However, pSA3239 lacks a corresponding conserved region (Fig. S2), and an analysis of the whole pSA3239 sequence also failed to reveal any region with signiﬁcant similarity to this conserved region. It seems, therefore, that although all the genes of the replication loci from these other linear plasmids are present in the telomere-adjacent position of pSA3239, this plasmid likely has a diﬀerent replication mechanism.

This is in agreement with the ﬁnding that, in contrast to the rather conserved replication mechanisms of the Streptomyces chromosomes, the replication machinery of the various linear plasmids is remarkably diverse, likely due to their disparate and diverse evolutionary origins (Kirby and Chen, 2011; Zhang et al., 2009). On the other hand, the telomeric end-patching replication mechanisms of these linear plasmids by the TP-Tap system are rather conserved (Bao and Cohen, 2003; Kirby and Chen, 2011; Yang et al., 2015). The region adjacent the left telo- mere of pSA3239 also contains the tpgSa and tapSa genes, encoding TP and Tap, respectively (Figs. 1, 4; Fig. S3)·Curiously, in the other Streptomyces linear plasmids named above, the TP and Tap homologues genes are all farther away, 14–26 kb from the replication initiation genes (Fig. 4). Most Streptomyces linear plasmids and chromosomes contain a tel- omere-located ttrA gene, encoding a protein with a DEAD box helicase motif. Inactivation of ttrA in the S. lividans linear plasmid SLP2 did not interfere with replication, but did aﬀect transfer eﬃciency, suggesting it has a role in conjugal transfer (Huang et al., 2003). All linear plas- mids similar to pSA3239 with end-located replication genes have a ttrA homologue at the distal end of the plasmid, but we could ﬁnd no ttrA homologue in pSA3239 itself; a transposase-encoding gene was found in its expected place (Fig. 4). It is therefore likely that the S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 chromosome itself contains a TtrA-encoding homologue, which is used in pSA3239 conjugal transfer.

In addition, we identiﬁed two genes, sa43 and sa44, coding for homologues of the ParA and ParB partition proteins (Fig. S4). The DNA- binding protein ParB and ATPase ParA are involved in the proper segregation replication (Mierzejewska and Jagura-Burdzy, 2012). The sa43 deletion did not aﬀect either growth or sporulation, and the mutant S. aureofaciens Δsa43 had a similar growth proﬁle as the wild- type strain (data not shown). We examined the stability of the S. aur- eofaciens Δsa43 mutant strain with the apramycin-resistance gene aac (3)IV replacing the parA homologous gene sa43 (Fig. S1). Our previous analysis of the partial sequence of pSA3239 revealed that it contains the type II PKS gene cluster aur1 for the angucycline antibiotic auricin, an NRPS gene cluster for the blue pigment in- digoidine, and the partial type II PKS gene cluster aur2 for an unknown secondary metabolite (Kormanec et al., 2014; Novakova et al., 2004, 2010, 2013). A genome mining analysis of the whole pSA3239 se- quence using antiSMASH 3.0 (Weber et al., 2015) revealed, in addition to these previously characterized gene clusters, two additional putative secondary metabolite gene clusters (Fig. 1, Table S1). The ﬁrst putative gene cluster, sa69–sa110, was similar to several NRPS/PKSI clusters, but all similarities were only to NRPS/PKSI gene clusters from bacterial genomes whose composition, status, and products were unknown. Moreover, these similarities were limited to only about 5% of the genes. An exception was the putative NRPS/PKSI gene cluster SSNG_07369 to SSNG_07516 from the contig of the Streptomyces sp. C genome (Acc. No. GG657752), where 21% of the genes showed similarities to the pSA3239 cluster. The NRPS Predictor identiﬁed the sa85 gene as en- coding a putative NRPS for cysteine, containing a condensation domain (residues 60–366), an adenylation domain (542–941), and a PCP do- main (1024–1090). Its closest homologue is to NRPS SSNG_07386 from Streptomyces sp. C, with 92% similarity and 87% identity (Table S1). However, based on these analyses alone, the actual compound syn- thesized by these proteins could not be predicted. Interestingly, a seven- gene subcluster of this cluster, sa91–sa97, is highly similar to part of the azoxy antibiotic valanimycin biosynthetic cluster vlm (Garg et al., 2002) (Fig. 6, Table S1). Valanimycin is synthesized from L-valine and L-serine via the intermediate isobutylhydroxylamine,

similar to part of the azoxy antibiotic valanimycin biosynthetic cluster vlm (Garg et al., 2002) (Fig. 6, Table S1). Valanimycin is synthesized from L-valine and L-serine via the intermediate isobutylhydroxylamine, which serves as an ac- ceptor for a seryl residue from seryl-tRNA. This unusual transfer reac- tion is catalyzed by the VlmA protein, producing the valanimycin in- termediate O-(L-seryl)isobutylhydroxylamine (Garg et al., 2008). The genes encoding both homologues of VlmA and seryl-tRNA synthase VlmL are present in this subcluster (Fig. 6), but the genes vlmJ and vlmK essential for the ﬁnal azoxy bond formation from the intermediate O-(L- seryl)isobutylhydroxylamine of valanimycin (Garg et al., 2009) are absent. Possibly, any compound produced by this putative pSA3239

secondary metabolite gene cluster may be synthesized using this in- termediate. However, a comparative analysis of the secondary meta- bolites produced by the wild-type S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 and a strain lacking pSA3239 (S. aureofaciens Del-LP) (see below) did not identify any product, except auricin and indigoidine, which was dependent upon pSA3239 under various growth conditions. Thus, this cluster, if it is, in fact, responsible for some compound, appears to be silent under these conditions. The second putative secondary metabolite gene cluster identiﬁed comprises genes sa127–sa131 (Fig. 1), and it appears to be a type I PKS gene cluster. The sa130 gene encodes a modular type I PKS with a KS domain (residues 22–438), an AT domain (541–838), a DH domain (901–1073), and an ACP domain (1231 − 1302). Its closest homologue was found in Streptomyces sp. C (putative type I PKS SSNG_07429), with 81% similarity and 86% identity (Table S1). However, no product has been determined for this putative PKS. This small cluster is likely not functional in the biosynthesis of a secondary metabolite, since aside from this type I PKS, it contains only three additional genes, encoding an esterase, an acyl CoA synthetase, and an ACP. 3.5. Another interesting feature of pSA3239 is its high abun- dance of transcriptional regulator genes (28 genes) from diﬀerent fa- milies, most of them located in the region between the aur1 and aur2 clusters (Fig. 1). There are ﬁve genes, sa37, sa35, aur1PR3, aur1PR2, and aur1PR4, encoding homologues from the SARP family of Strepto- myces antibiotic regulatory proteins (Wietzorrek and Bibb, 1997). Two of these, aur1PR3 and aur1PR4, have previously been shown to regulate auricin biosynthesis (Kormanec et al., 2014). Disruption of the other three SARP genes, however, had no eﬀect on auricin or indigoidine production (Novakova et al., 2011; Kormanec, unpublished results). Eleven genes, sa40, sa38, sa36, aur1R, aur1B, sa100, sa126, sa137, sa148, sa176, and sa182, encode proteins highly similar to those from the TetR family of transcriptional repressors (Cuthbertson and Nodwell, 2013). One of them, aur1R, has been shown to negatively regulate auricin production (Kormanec et al., 2014). Two other genes, sa42 and sagR, encode proteins very similar to the gamma-butyrolactone auto- regulator-receptor subfamily of TetR (Takano, 2006). In particular, sagR has been veriﬁed to be part of the sagAR gamma-butyrolactone autoregulator-receptor auricin production (Mingyar et al., 2015). Disruption of the other homologue, sa42, had no eﬀect on auricin production (Kormanec, unpublished results). Two genes, sa28 and sa144, encode homologues of the AraC/XylS family (Gallegos et al., 1997); two other

other homologue, sa42, had no eﬀect on auricin production (Kormanec, unpublished results). Two genes, sa28 and sa144, encode homologues of the AraC/XylS family (Gallegos et al., 1997); two other translationally-coupled genes, sa173 and sa174, encode proteins highly similar to the response regulators and sensor histidine kinases of the bacterial two-component regulatory systems involved in transducing signals from external or internal con- ditions into the expression of particular genes (Stock et al., 2000). In addition, four other genes encode putative regulators from four dif- ferent families; the sa64 gene MarR (pfam12802), the sa160 gene ArsR (cd00090), the sa104 gene XRE (cd00093), and the sa67 gene LuxR (cd06170) (Table S1). The large number of putative regulators may indicate that some of these possible other pathways are subject to the same sort of stringent regulation as auricin (Kormanec et al., 2014).

Interestingly, one of the pSA3239 genes, sa62, encodes a protein highly similar to the ECF sigma factors of RNA polymerase. The highest similarities were, again, to unknown ECF sigma factors from various actinomycetes genomes. The highest similarity (82% identity and 91% similarity) was to the putative ECF sigma factor SigX4 from S. leeu- wenhoekii (Table S1). Since several ECF sigma factors have recently been shown to regulate antibiotics production in actinomycetes (Luo et al., 2014; Seipke et al., 2014; Sherwood and Bibb, 2013), we identiﬁed three transposase genes disrupted the sa62 gene using REDIRECT methodology (Gust et al., 2003) and investigated the production of auricin in the mutant strain. However, the disruption did not signiﬁcantly aﬀect auricin production, and the mutant strain was phenotypically indistinguishable from the wild-type strain (data not shown). The ﬁnal interesting feature of pSA3239 is the presence of 10 genes, sa113–sa122, encoding proteins similar to several enzymes involved in sulfur metabolism and transport (Fig. 1, Table S1). 3.6. Phenotype of a S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 strain lacking pSA3239

We previously found that pSA3239 is quite stable in S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 (Novakova et al., 2013). An analysis of 300 independent colonies from a spore stock of S. aureofaciens ΔbpsA1 mutant strain with the pSA3239 bpsA gene replaced by the apramycin-resistance gene aac (3)IV (Novakova et al., 2010), prepared after two rounds of non-se- lective sporulation, found only apramycin-resistant colonies. In order to prepare an S. aureofaciens strain lacking pSA3239, we used a similar strategy, this time employing several previously studied S. aureofaciens mutant strains, in which one of the auricin genes, aur1PR3, sagA, sagR, sa46, sa53, sa59, or sa52, had been replaced by the apramycin-re- sistance gene (Bekeova et al., 2016; Mingyar et al., 2015; Novakova et al., 2011). After analyzing thousands of colonies, we identiﬁed one apramycin-sensitive colony. The corresponding strain was named S. aureofaciens Del-LP. The absence of pSA3239 was conﬁrmed by PFGE followed a by hybridization analysis with DIG-labelled probe from pSA3239. Furthermore, a standard Southern blot hybridization of S. aureofaciens Del-LP chromosomal DNA using the DIG –labelled probes from three diﬀerent positions in pSA3239 (left-end, center, right end) showed no signal, even after long exposure (Fig. S5). A phenotypic analysis of S. aureofaciens Del-LP revealed no signiﬁcant diﬀerences in growth and diﬀerentiation compared to wild-type S. aureofaciens CCM 3239. Analysis of secondary metabolites from both strains grown in rich Bennet liquid medium by HPLC and TLC followed by biochromato- graphy revealed no diﬀerences in HPLC proﬁles and TLC spots, aside from the expected lack of auricin and indigoidine in S. aureofaciens Del-

Bennet liquid medium by HPLC and TLC followed by biochromato- graphy revealed no diﬀerences in HPLC proﬁles and TLC spots, aside from the expected lack of auricin and indigoidine in S. aureofaciens Del- LP (Fig. S6). Therefore, either the other putative secondary metabolite gene clusters identiﬁed in pSA3239 are likely to be silent under these growth conditions, or the gene clusters are not functional.

In this report, we presented the complete nucleotide sequence of the S. aureofaciens CCM 3239 linear plasmid pSA3239 and a bioinformatics analysis of its 241,076-bp nucleotide sequence, with particular focus on replication, segregation, and secondary metabolite production. We identiﬁed and characterized its unprecedentedly small (13 bp) telo- meric sequence, CCCGCGGAGCGGG, which is identical to the con- served Palindrome I involved in priming end-patching replication. We identiﬁed a pair of replication initiation genes located at the extreme left end of the plasmid, which, together with similar genes from several other linear plasmids, constitute a new family of replication initiation proteins. This indicates that the Streptomyces linear plasmids have an unexpected variety of components, positions and combinations of re- plication loci. Two genes homologous to the parAB partitioning system were identiﬁed in pSA3239, and deletion of the parA homologue re- sulted in a dramatically reduced and inappropriate distribution of the plasmid, conﬁrming its role in pSA3239 partitioning and stability. A bioinformatics analysis identiﬁed ﬁve secondary metabolite gene clus- ters in pSA3239. In addition to the previously characterized aur1 gene cluster for the biosynthesis of the angucycline antibiotic auricin and the NRPS gene cluster responsible for the blue pigment indigoidine, the plasmid also contains the partial type II PKS gene cluster aur2, a partial type I PKS gene cluster, and an NRPS/PKSI gene cluster, all of them producing unknown secondary metabolites. Together with the high number (28) of regulatory genes from various families, these indicate

that pSA3239 has an unusually condensed gene organization for sec- ondary metabolism, similar to the linear plasmid pSLA2-L from S. rochei (Mochizuki et al., 2003). We prepared a S. aureofaciens strain lacking pSA3239 and investigated its secondary metabolite production in comparison with that of the wild-type strain and found that no com- pounds, other than auricin and indigoidine were dependent upon pSA3239, suggesting that these three gene clusters may be silent under laboratory conditions, though they may still be activated by some other, unknown environmental signals. doi.org/10.1016/j.gene.2017.11.046.
